My own take on a Super Heavy aerial transport for Space Marines dubbed the Storm Crane. Sized to be used in Epic/Legion Imperialis games.

Unique in its role, Storm Cranes are able to deliver a variety of assets to the front. From 10 fully embarked rhinos, or 4 kratos heavy battle tanks or any other armored detachment, Storm Cranes are able to bring full detachments of armor needed on the battle field. Protected by heavy plating and a pair of void shields this flyer can withstand any punishment short of anti-titan weapons. Ensuring its cargo successfully arrives where it is needed. Each Strom Crane is armed with two audax heavy bolter arrays and two titan sized havoc launchers making it a formidable assault craft that can break through enemy lines. A truly armored work horse, Space Marine legions relied heavily on these vehicles throughout the crusade and into the Heresy.


While I designed most of this using 3D Builder, I did borrow some choice parts from free kits.
Winglets/Audax Turrets from MKHand Industries
Thruster Turbine and Exhaust from IronMaster
Titan Hatch and Void Shields from Danny_Cyanide

They are great little free files and will work well at 8mm. I sized them to have roughly a 70mm wingspan, but size however you like, just be cognicent that resizing circles can make ovals.

This cobbled-together flying piece of scrap metal looks as if it should fall apart under a gentle breeze. And yet, it barrels through the air with wild abandon; bullets, bombs and stranger projectiles flying from it in all directions. A mighty flying fortress, this super-scrap bomber all but ignores incoming fire as it passes harmlessly through open superstructure, or as it blasts away rusty plating that was all but falling off anyway, leaving critical structures safe below layers of bolted on scrap metal.

This 67 piece multi-part kit comes with a huge range of options. It can be built with two wing profiles, alternative hulls with differing tailfins, and a range of options for turrets and bombs, many of which can be mirrored for additional variety / symmetry. It includes monstrous 'bouncing bombs' for some truly 'wild' bombing runs!

The kit is designed to be scaled to 8mm scale model games, such as plane warfare games, or those featuring legions of models fighting. It could also be used in 6mm games where Epic Marines fight in Space, a real armageddon level battle. Compatable with ork style armies, it would be a great proxy for a mega bommber or landa. It is sufficiently detailed that an ambitious hobbyist could print it at 400% scale to create a huge center piece model or terrain for 32mm games set in grim dark universes. This would of course require additional cuts to the model!

I am a hobbyist 3D modeller - not a professional 3D designed. However, this project has taken many, many hours of development, test printing and correction. It is my first 'paid for' model, a reflection of the time it took to create. Almost all my other models are currently available for free, so please do look through those if you are interested in further supporting me and my hobby.

I also welcome feedback and will look to develop this model with improvments and additional options in future.

A conversion kit to turn your regular Aeronautica Imperialis Tiger Sharks (such as from starter set) into AX-1-0 with heavy weapon versions.

For each Tiger Shark, you will need to print:
2x weapons
2x connector pieces
2x body components (you will need to mirror one of these, the other parts don't require mirroring)

To assemble, make sure to SKIP steps 8 and 9 in the Tiger Shark assembly instructions booklet (don't glue in the weapons or missile bays). Glue your printed weapon, connector, and body pieces together, then slot into the areas where the normal weapon and missile bay components would go. They won't friction fit so you will need to glue or magnetise once you're sure they are aligned properly.

The Heavy Rail hasn't worked particularly well on my FDM printer, particularly the interior gap detail. You may have more luck with something more dialed in or with a resin printer.

The Heavy Plasma worked well with FDM once I removed the venting fins from the underside. I've attached the finned versions in case you have more luck.
